# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: accelerometer-mems
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] An **accelerometer** is a device that measures the proper acceleration of an object.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Proper acceleration is the acceleration (the rate of change of velocity) of the object relative to an observer who is in free fall (that is, relative to an inertial frame of reference).
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Proper acceleration is different from coordinate acceleration, which is acceleration with respect to a given coordinate system, which may or may not be accelerating.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] For example, an accelerometer at rest on the surface of the Earth will measure an acceleration due to Earth's gravity straight upwards of about *g* ≈ 9.81 m/s2.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] By contrast, an accelerometer that is in free fall will measure zero acceleration.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Highly sensitive accelerometers are used in inertial navigation systems for aircraft and missiles.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] In unmanned aerial vehicles, accelerometers help to stabilize flight.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Micromachined micro-electromechanical systems (MEMS) accelerometers are used in handheld electronic devices such as smartphones, cameras and video-game controllers to detect movement and orientation of these devices.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Vibration in industrial machinery is monitored by accelerometers.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Seismometers are sensitive accelerometers for monitoring ground movement such as earthquakes.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] When two or more accelerometers are coordinated with one another, they can measure differences in proper acceleration, particularly gravity, over their separation in space—that is, the gradient of the gravitational field.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Gravity gradiometry is useful because absolute gravity is a weak effect and depends on the local density of the Earth, which is quite variable.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] A single-axis accelerometer measures acceleration along a specified axis.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] A multi-axis accelerometer detects both the magnitude and the direction of the proper acceleration, as a vector quantity, and is usually implemented as several single-axis accelerometers oriented along different axes.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] An accelerometer measures proper acceleration, which is the acceleration it experiences relative to freefall and is the acceleration felt by people and objects.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Put another way, at any point in spacetime the equivalence principle guarantees the existence of a local inertial frame, and an accelerometer measures the acceleration relative to that frame.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Such accelerations are popularly denoted g-force; i.e., in comparison to standard gravity.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] An accelerometer at rest relative to the Earth's surface will indicate approximately 1 g *upwards* because the Earth's surface exerts a normal force upwards relative to the local inertial frame (the frame of a freely falling object near the surface).
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] To obtain the acceleration due to motion with respect to the Earth, this "gravity offset" must be subtracted and corrections made for effects caused by the Earth's rotation relative to the inertial frame.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] The reason for the appearance of a gravitational offset is Einstein's equivalence principle, which states that the effects of gravity on an object are indistinguishable from acceleration.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] When held fixed in a gravitational field by, for example, applying a ground reaction force or an equivalent upward thrust, the reference frame for an accelerometer (its own casing) accelerates upwards with respect to a free-falling reference frame.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] For similar reasons, an accelerometer will read *zero* during any type of free fall.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] This includes use in a coasting spaceship in deep space far from any mass, a spaceship orbiting the Earth, an airplane in a parabolic "zero-g" arc, or any free-fall in a vacuum.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Another example is free-fall at a sufficiently high altitude that atmospheric effects can be neglected.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] However, this does not include a (non-free) fall in which air resistance produces drag forces that reduce the acceleration until constant terminal velocity is reached.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] At terminal velocity, the accelerometer will indicate 1 g acceleration upwards.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] For the same reason a skydiver, upon reaching terminal velocity, does not feel as though he or she were in "free-fall", but rather experiences a feeling similar to being supported (at 1 g) on a "bed" of uprushing air.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Acceleration is quantified in the SI unit metres per second per second (m/s2), in the cgs unit gal (Gal), or popularly in terms of standard gravity (*g*).
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] For the practical purpose of finding the acceleration of objects with respect to the Earth, such as for use in an inertial navigation system, a knowledge of local gravity is required.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] This can be obtained either by calibrating the device at rest, or from a known model of gravity at the approximate current position.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] A basic mechanical accelerometer is a damped proof mass on a spring.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] When the accelerometer experiences an acceleration, Newton's third law causes the spring's compression (or extension) to adjust to exert an equivalent force on the mass to counteract the acceleration.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Since the spring's force scales linearly with the length change (according to Hooke's law) and because the spring constant and mass are known constants, a measurement of the spring's compression (or extension) is also a measurement of acceleration.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] The system is damped to prevent oscillations of the mass and spring interfering with measurements.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] However, the damping causes accelerometers to have a frequency response.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Many animals have sensory organs to detect acceleration, especially gravity.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] In these, the proof mass is usually one or more crystals of calcium carbonate otoliths (Latin for "ear stone") or statoconia, acting against a bed of hairs connected to neurons.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] The hairs form the springs, with the neurons as sensors.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Many vertebrates, including humans, have these structures in their inner ears.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Most invertebrates have similar organs, but not as part of their hearing organs.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Mechanical accelerometers are often designed so that an electronic circuit senses a small amount of motion, then pushes on the proof mass with some type of linear motor to keep the proof mass from moving far.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] The motor might be an electromagnet or in very small accelerometers, electrostatic.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Since the circuit's electronic behavior can be carefully designed, and the proof mass does not move far, these designs can be very stable (i.e. they do not oscillate), very linear with a controlled frequency response.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] In mechanical accelerometers, measurement is often electrical, piezoelectric, piezoresistive or capacitive.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Piezoelectric accelerometers use piezoceramic sensors (e.g. lead zirconate titanate) or single crystals (e.g. quartz, tourmaline).
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] They are unmatched in high frequency measurements, low packaged weight, and resistance to high temperatures.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Piezoresistive accelerometers resist shock (very high accelerations) better.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Capacitive accelerometers typically use a silicon micro-machined sensing element.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Modern mechanical accelerometers are often small *micro-electro-mechanical systems* (MEMS), and are often very simple MEMS devices, consisting of little more than a cantilever beam with a proof mass (also known as *seismic mass*).
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Damping results from the residual gas sealed in the device.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] As long as the Q-factor is not too low, damping does not result in a lower sensitivity.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Under the influence of external accelerations, the proof mass deflects from its neutral position.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] This deflection is measured in an analog or digital manner.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Most commonly, the capacitance between a set of fixed beams and a set of beams attached to the proof mass is measured.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] This method is simple, reliable, and inexpensive.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Integrating piezoresistors in the springs to detect spring deformation, and thus deflection, is a good alternative, although a few more process steps are needed during the fabrication sequence.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] For very high sensitivities quantum tunnelling is also used; this requires a dedicated process making it very expensive.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Optical measurement has been demonstrated in laboratory devices.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Another MEMS-based accelerometer is a thermal (or convective) accelerometer.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] It contains a small heater in a very small dome.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] This heats the air or other fluid inside the dome.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] The thermal bubble acts as the proof mass.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] An accompanying temperature sensor (like a thermistor; or thermopile) in the dome measures the temperature in one location of the dome.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] This measures the location of the heated bubble within the dome.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] When the dome is accelerated, the colder, higher density fluid pushes the heated bubble.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] The temperature measurement is interpreted as acceleration.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Gravity acting on the fluid provides the spring.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Since the proof mass is very lightweight gas, and not held by a beam or lever, thermal accelerometers can survive high shocks.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Another variation uses a wire to both heat the gas and detect the change in temperature.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] The change of temperature changes the resistance of the wire.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] A two dimensional accelerometer can be economically constructed with one dome, one bubble and two measurement devices.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Most micromechanical accelerometers operate *in-plane*, that is, they are designed to be sensitive only to a direction in the plane of the die.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] By integrating two devices perpendicularly on a single die a two-axis accelerometer can be made.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] By adding another *out-of-plane* device, three axes can be measured.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Such a combination may have much lower misalignment error than three discrete models combined after packaging.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Micromechanical accelerometers are available in a wide variety of measuring ranges, reaching up to thousands of *g*'s.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] The designer must compromise between sensitivity and the maximum acceleration that can be measured.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Accelerometers can be used to measure vehicle acceleration.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Accelerometers can be used to measure vibration on cars, machines, buildings, process control systems and safety installations.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] They can also be used to measure seismic activity, inclination, machine vibration, dynamic distance and speed with or without the influence of gravity.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Applications for accelerometers that measure gravity, wherein an accelerometer is specifically configured for use in gravimetry, are called gravimeters.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Accelerometers are also increasingly used in the biological sciences.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] High frequency recordings of bi-axial or tri-axial acceleration allows the discrimination of behavioral patterns while animals are out of sight.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] For example, accelerometers have been used to study flight energy expenditure of Harris's Hawk (*Parabuteo unicinctus*).
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Researchers are also using smartphone accelerometers to collect and extract mechano-biological descriptors of resistance exercise.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Increasingly, researchers are deploying accelerometers with additional technology, such as cameras or microphones, to better understand animal behaviour in the wild (for example, hunting behaviour of Canada lynx).
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Accelerometers are also used for machinery health monitoring to report the vibration and its changes in time of shafts at the bearings of rotating equipment such as turbines, pumps, fans, rollers, compressors, or bearing fault which, if not attended to promptly, can lead to costly repairs.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Accelerometer vibration data allows the user to monitor machines and detect these faults before the rotating equipment fails completely.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Accelerometers are widely used in structural health monitoring (SHM) of buildings, bridges and other civil infrastructure to record the dynamic response under ambient and forced loads (e.g., wind, traffic, machinery and earthquakes).
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] From these vibration records, engineers estimate modal properties—natural frequencies, damping ratios and mode shapes—often using operational modal analysis (OMA) techniques for in-service structures.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] These parameters are trended over time for condition assessment and model updating.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] In seismic regions, arrays of accelerometers installed in buildings and other structures provide strong-motion data for rapid post-event assessments and long-term performance studies.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Geological Survey's National Strong-Motion Project (NSMP) operates structural arrays and distributes building and structural records via the Center for Engineering Strong Motion Data (CESMD).
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Instrumentation and data-quality practices for building vibration measurements are guided by international standards.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] ISO 4866 provides principles for measuring the vibration of fixed structures and evaluating vibration effects based on structural response, while ISO 10137 gives serviceability recommendations for buildings and walkways with respect to human perception, contents and the structure itself.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Choice of accelerometer technology depends on frequency range and amplitude.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Piezoelectric accelerometers are common for higher-frequency, higher-amplitude measurements, whereas low-noise MEMS accelerometers have become attractive for low-frequency building and bridge monitoring and for dense or wireless deployments due to cost and power advantages.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Recent evaluations and developments show that appropriately selected MEMS devices can identify modal parameters with acceptable accuracy for SHM and have been integrated into high-sensitivity wireless nodes.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Networked and wireless smart-sensor approaches allow distributed monitoring at scale.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Reviews document the shift from wired to wireless SHM systems and the maturation of wireless smart-sensor networks for tasks such as ambient-vibration modal identification and continuous trending.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Accelerometers are often fused with other sensors to improve displacement and drift estimation, especially for large or flexible structures.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] GNSS provides quasi-static and very-low-frequency motion that complements accelerometer-based dynamics; recent studies report accurate dynamic displacement retrieval using high-rate or multi-GNSS solutions combined with accelerometers.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Beyond permanently instrumented assets, indirect and crowdsourced approaches using smartphone accelerometers have been explored, particularly for bridges.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Research has shown that modal frequencies—and in some cases spatial vibration characteristics—can be estimated from accelerometer data collected by vehicles crossing bridges, offering a complementary, low-cost screening tool for large inventories.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Related work has also evaluated smartphone-based ambient vibration monitoring of buildings.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Long-term case studies illustrate large-scale deployments.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Hong Kong's Wind and Structural Health Monitoring System (WASHMS) has instrumented the Tsing Ma Bridge since 1997; subsequent publications report decades of monitoring for load and response in service.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Scotland's Queensferry Crossing was equipped with a comprehensive SHM system including thousands of sensors, and Sydney Harbour Bridge has been reported as instrumented with thousands of sensors for real-time monitoring.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] SHM data are used for continuous condition tracking, event-triggered assessments (e.g., after earthquakes), and to support asset management decisions.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] In bridge engineering, guidance from transportation agencies describes how field data—including accelerometer measurements—can be integrated with inspection and nondestructive evaluation to improve load-rating reliability and maintenance planning.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Zoll's AED Plus uses CPR-D•padz which contain an accelerometer to measure the depth of CPR chest compressions.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Within the last several years, several companies have produced and marketed sports watches for runners that include footpods, containing accelerometers to help determine the speed and distance for the runner wearing the unit.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] In Belgium, accelerometer-based step counters are promoted by the government to encourage people to walk a few thousand steps each day.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Herman Digital Trainer uses accelerometers to measure strike force in physical training.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] It has been suggested to build football helmets with accelerometers in order to measure the impact of head collisions.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] The US Army Research Laboratory developed the Three-Axis Acceleration Switch which has been suggested for this application.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Accelerometers have been used to calculate gait parameters, such as stance and swing phase.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] This kind of sensor can be used to measure or monitor people.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] An inertial navigation system is a navigation aid that uses a computer and motion sensors (accelerometers) to continuously calculate via dead reckoning the position, orientation, and velocity (direction and speed of movement) of a moving object without the need for external references.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Other terms used to refer to inertial navigation systems or closely related devices include inertial guidance system, inertial reference platform, and many other variations.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] An accelerometer alone is unsuitable to determine changes in altitude over distances where the vertical decrease of gravity is significant, such as for aircraft and rockets.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] In the presence of a gravitational gradient, the calibration and data reduction process is numerically unstable.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Accelerometers are used to detect apogee in both professional and in amateur rocketry.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Accelerometers are also being used in Intelligent Compaction rollers.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Accelerometers are used alongside gyroscopes in inertial navigation systems.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] One of the most common uses for MEMS accelerometers is in airbag deployment systems for modern automobiles.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] In this case, the accelerometers are used to detect the rapid negative acceleration of the vehicle to determine when a collision has occurred and the severity of the collision.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Another common automotive use is in electronic stability control systems, which use a lateral accelerometer to measure cornering forces.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] The widespread use of accelerometers in the automotive industry has pushed their cost down dramatically.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Another automotive application is the monitoring of noise, vibration, and harshness (NVH), conditions that cause discomfort for drivers and passengers and may also be indicators of mechanical faults.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Tilting trains use accelerometers and gyroscopes to calculate the required tilt.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Modern electronic accelerometers are used in remote sensing devices intended for the monitoring of active volcanoes to detect the motion of magma.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Accelerometers are increasingly being incorporated into personal electronic devices to detect the orientation of the device, for example, a display screen.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] A *free-fall sensor* (FFS) is an accelerometer used to detect if a system has been dropped and is falling.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] It can then apply safety measures such as parking the head of a hard disk to prevent a head crash and resulting data loss upon impact.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] This device is included in the many common computer and consumer electronic products that are produced by a variety of manufacturers.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] It is also used in some data loggers to monitor handling operations for shipping containers.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] The length of time in free fall is used to calculate the height of drop and to estimate the shock to the package.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Some smartphones, digital audio players and personal digital assistants contain accelerometers for user interface control; often the accelerometer is used to present landscape or portrait views of the device's screen, based on the way the device is being held.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Apple has included an accelerometer in every generation of iPhone, iPad, and iPod touch, as well as in every iPod nano since the 4th generation.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Along with orientation view adjustment, accelerometers in mobile devices can also be used as pedometers, in conjunction with specialized applications.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Automatic Collision Notification (ACN) systems also use accelerometers in a system to call for help in event of a vehicle crash.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Prominent ACN systems include OnStar AACN service, Ford Link's 911 Assist, Toyota's Safety Connect, Lexus Link, or BMW Assist.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Many accelerometer-equipped smartphones also have ACN software available for download.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] ACN systems are activated by detecting crash-strength accelerations.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Accelerometers are used in vehicle Electronic stability control systems to measure the vehicle's actual movement.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] A computer compares the vehicle's actual movement to the driver's steering and throttle input.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] The stability control computer can selectively brake individual wheels and/or reduce engine power to minimize the difference between driver input and the vehicle's actual movement.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] This can help prevent the vehicle from spinning or rolling over.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Some pedometers use an accelerometer to more accurately measure the number of steps taken and distance traveled than a mechanical sensor can provide.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Nintendo's Wii video game console uses a controller called a Wii Remote that contains a three-axis accelerometer and was designed primarily for motion input.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Users also have the option of buying an additional motion-sensitive attachment, the Nunchuk, so that motion input could be recorded from both of the user's hands independently.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Is also used on the Nintendo 3DS system.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Sleep phase alarm clocks use accelerometric sensors to detect movement of a sleeper, so that it can wake the person when he/she is not in REM phase, in order to awaken the person more easily.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] A microphone or eardrum is a membrane that responds to oscillations in air pressure.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] These oscillations cause acceleration, so accelerometers can be used to record sound.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] A 2012 study found that voices can be detected in 93% of typical daily situations by accelerometers like those in smartphones fixed to the sternum.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Conversely, carefully designed sounds can cause accelerometers to report false data.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] One study tested 20 models of (MEMS) smartphone accelerometers and found that a majority were susceptible to this attack.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] A number of 21st-century devices use accelerometers to align the screen depending on the direction the device is held (e.g., switching between portrait and landscape modes).
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Such devices include many tablet PCs and some smartphones and digital cameras.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] The Amida Simputer, a handheld Linux device launched in 2004, was the first commercial handheld to have a built-in accelerometer.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] It incorporated many gesture-based interactions using this accelerometer, including page-turning, zoom-in and zoom-out of images, change of portrait to landscape mode, and many simple gesture-based games.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] As of January 2009, almost all new mobile phones and digital cameras contain at least a tilt sensor and sometimes an accelerometer for the purpose of auto image rotation, motion-sensitive mini-games, and correcting shake when taking photographs.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Camcorders use accelerometers for image stabilization, either by moving optical elements to adjust the light path to the sensor to cancel out unintended motions or digitally shifting the image to smooth out detected motion.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Some stills cameras use accelerometers for anti-blur capturing.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] The camera holds off capturing the image when the camera is moving.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] When the camera is still (if only for a millisecond, as could be the case for vibration), the image is captured.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] An example of the application of this technology is the Glogger VS2, a phone application which runs on Symbian based phones with accelerometers such as the Nokia N96.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Some digital cameras contain accelerometers to determine the orientation of the photo being taken and also for rotating the current picture when viewing.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Many laptops feature an accelerometer which is used to detect drops.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] If a drop is detected, the heads of the hard disk are parked to avoid data loss and possible head or disk damage by the ensuing shock.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] A gravimeter, or gravitometer, is an instrument used in gravimetry for measuring the local gravitational field.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] A gravimeter is a type of accelerometer, except that accelerometers are susceptible to all vibrations including noise, that cause oscillatory accelerations.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] This is counteracted in the gravimeter by integral vibration isolation and signal processing.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Though the essential principle of design is the same as in accelerometers, gravimeters are typically designed to be much more sensitive than accelerometers in order to measure very tiny changes within the Earth's gravity, of 1 *g*.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] In contrast, other accelerometers are often designed to measure 1000 *g* or more, and many perform multi-axial measurements.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] The constraints on temporal resolution are usually less for gravimeters, so that resolution can be increased by processing the output with a longer "time constant".
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] If done without a user's knowledge or consent, this is referred to as an inference attack.
[src:accelerometer-mems/accelerometer] Additionally, millions of smartphones could be vulnerable to software cracking via accelerometers.
[src:accelerometer-mems/comb-drive] The attractive electrostatic forces are created when a voltage is applied between the static and moving combs causing them to be drawn together.
[src:accelerometer-mems/comb-drive] The force developed by the actuator is proportional to the change in capacitance between the two combs, increasing with driving voltage, the number of comb teeth, and the gap between the teeth.
[src:accelerometer-mems/comb-drive] The combs are arranged so that they never touch (because then there would be no voltage difference).
[src:accelerometer-mems/comb-drive] Typically the teeth are arranged so that they can slide past one another until each tooth occupies the slot in the opposite comb.
[src:accelerometer-mems/comb-drive] Restoring springs, levers, and crankshafts can be added if the motor's linear operation is to be converted to rotation or other motions.
[src:accelerometer-mems/comb-drive] The force can be derived by first starting with the energy stored in a capacitor and then differentiating in the direction of the force.
[src:accelerometer-mems/comb-drive] V = applied electric potential, $\epsilon _{r}$ = relative permittivity of dielectric, $\epsilon _{o}$ = permittivity of free space (8.85 pF/m), n = total number of fingers on both sides of electrodes, t = thickness in the out-of-plane direction of the electrodes, d = gap between electrodes.
[src:accelerometer-mems/comb-drive] Comb drives cannot scale to large gap distances (equivalently actuation distance), since development of effective forces at large gaps distances would require high voltages—therefore limited by electrical breakdown.
[src:accelerometer-mems/comb-drive] More importantly, limitations imposed by gap distance limits the actuation distance.
[src:accelerometer-mems/piezoelectric-accelerometer] A **piezoelectric accelerometer** is an accelerometer that employs the piezoelectric effect of certain materials to measure dynamic changes in mechanical variables (e.g., acceleration, vibration, and mechanical shock).
[src:accelerometer-mems/piezoelectric-accelerometer] As with all transducers, piezoelectrics convert one form of energy into another and provide an electrical signal in response to a quantity, property, or condition that is being measured.
[src:accelerometer-mems/piezoelectric-accelerometer] Using the general sensing method upon which all accelerometers are based, acceleration acts upon a seismic mass that is restrained by a spring or suspended on a cantilever beam, and converts a physical force into an electrical signal.
[src:accelerometer-mems/piezoelectric-accelerometer] Before the acceleration can be converted into an electrical quantity it must first be converted into either a force or displacement.
[src:accelerometer-mems/piezoelectric-accelerometer] This conversion is done via the mass spring system shown in the figure to the right.
[src:accelerometer-mems/piezoelectric-accelerometer] The word piezoelectric finds its roots in the Greek word *piezein*, which means to squeeze or press.
[src:accelerometer-mems/piezoelectric-accelerometer] When a physical force is exerted on the accelerometer, the seismic mass loads the piezoelectric element according to Newton's second law of motion ( $F=ma$ ).
[src:accelerometer-mems/piezoelectric-accelerometer] The force exerted on the piezoelectric material can be observed in the change in the electrostatic force or voltage generated by the piezoelectric material.
[src:accelerometer-mems/piezoelectric-accelerometer] This differs from a piezoresistive effect in that piezoresistive materials experience a change in the resistance of the material rather than a change in charge or voltage.
[src:accelerometer-mems/piezoelectric-accelerometer] Physical force exerted on the piezoelectric can be classified as one of two types; bending or compression.
[src:accelerometer-mems/piezoelectric-accelerometer] Stress of the compression type can be understood as a force exerted to one side of the piezoelectric while the opposing side rests against a fixed surface, while bending involves a force being exerted on the piezoelectric from both sides.
[src:accelerometer-mems/piezoelectric-accelerometer] Piezoelectric materials used for the purpose of accelerometers fall into two categories: single crystal and ceramic materials.
[src:accelerometer-mems/piezoelectric-accelerometer] The first and more widely used are single-crystal materials (usually quartz).
[src:accelerometer-mems/piezoelectric-accelerometer] Though these materials do offer a long life span in terms of sensitivity, their disadvantage is that they are generally less sensitive than some piezoelectric ceramics.
[src:accelerometer-mems/piezoelectric-accelerometer] The other category, ceramic materials, have a higher piezoelectric constant (sensitivity) than single-crystal materials, and are less expensive to produce.
[src:accelerometer-mems/piezoelectric-accelerometer] Ceramics use barium titanate, lead-zirconate-lead-titanate, lead metaniobate, and other materials whose composition is considered proprietary by the company responsible for their development.
[src:accelerometer-mems/piezoelectric-accelerometer] The disadvantage of piezoelectric ceramics, however, is that their sensitivity degrades with time making the longevity of the device less than that of single-crystal materials.
[src:accelerometer-mems/piezoelectric-accelerometer] In applications when low sensitivity piezoelectrics are used, two or more crystals can be connected together for output multiplication.
[src:accelerometer-mems/piezoelectric-accelerometer] The proper material can be chosen for particular applications based on the sensitivity, frequency response, bulk-resistivity, and thermal response.
[src:accelerometer-mems/piezoelectric-accelerometer] Due to the low output signal and high output impedance that piezoelectric accelerometers possess, there is a need for amplification and impedance conversion of the signal produced.
[src:accelerometer-mems/piezoelectric-accelerometer] In the past this problem has been solved using a separate (external) amplifier/impedance converter.
[src:accelerometer-mems/piezoelectric-accelerometer] This method, however, is generally impractical due to the noise that is introduced as well as the physical and environmental constraints posed on the system as a result.
[src:accelerometer-mems/piezoelectric-accelerometer] Today IC amplifiers/impedance converters are commercially available and are generally packaged within the case of the accelerometer itself.
[src:accelerometer-mems/piezoelectric-accelerometer] Behind the mystery of the operation of the piezoelectric accelerometer lie some very fundamental concepts governing the behavior of crystallographic structures.
[src:accelerometer-mems/piezoelectric-accelerometer] In 1880, Pierre and Jacques Curie published an experimental demonstration connecting mechanical stress and surface charge on a crystal.
[src:accelerometer-mems/piezoelectric-accelerometer] This phenomenon became known as the piezoelectric effect.
[src:accelerometer-mems/piezoelectric-accelerometer] Closely related to this phenomenon is the Curie point, named for the physicist Pierre Curie, which is the temperature above which piezoelectric material loses spontaneous polarization of its atoms.
[src:accelerometer-mems/piezoelectric-accelerometer] The development of the commercial piezoelectric accelerometer came about through a number of attempts to find the most effective method to measure the vibration on large structures such as bridges and on vehicles in motion such as aircraft.
[src:accelerometer-mems/piezoelectric-accelerometer] One attempt involved using the resistance strain gage as a device to build an accelerometer.
[src:accelerometer-mems/piezoelectric-accelerometer] Meier who, through his work at MIT, is given credit as the first to construct a commercial strain gage accelerometer (circa 1938).
[src:accelerometer-mems/piezoelectric-accelerometer] However, the strain gage accelerometers were fragile and could only produce low resonant frequencies and they also exhibited a low frequency response.
[src:accelerometer-mems/piezoelectric-accelerometer] These limitations in dynamic range made it unsuitable for testing naval aircraft structures.
[src:accelerometer-mems/piezoelectric-accelerometer] On the other hand, the piezoelectric sensor was proven to be a much better choice over the strain gage in designing an accelerometer.
[src:accelerometer-mems/piezoelectric-accelerometer] The high modulus of elasticity of piezoelectric materials makes the piezoelectric sensor a more viable solution to the problems identified with the strain gage accelerometer.
[src:accelerometer-mems/piezoelectric-accelerometer] Simply stated, the inherent properties of the piezoelectric accelerometers made it a much better alternative to the strain gage types because of its high frequency response, and its ability to generate high resonant frequencies.
[src:accelerometer-mems/piezoelectric-accelerometer] The piezoelectric accelerometer allowed for a reduction in its physical size at the manufacturing level and it also provided for a higher g (standard gravity) capability relative to the strain gage type.
[src:accelerometer-mems/piezoelectric-accelerometer] By comparison, the strain gage type exhibited a flat frequency response up to 200 Hz while the piezoelectric type provided a flat response up to 10,000 Hz.
[src:accelerometer-mems/piezoelectric-accelerometer] These improvements made it possible for measuring the high frequency vibrations associated with the quick movements and short duration shocks of aircraft which before was not possible with the strain gage types.
[src:accelerometer-mems/piezoelectric-accelerometer] Before long, the technological benefits of the piezoelectric accelerometer became apparent and in the late 1940s, large scale production of piezoelectric accelerometers began.
[src:accelerometer-mems/piezoelectric-accelerometer] Today, piezoelectric accelerometers are used for instrumentation in the fields of engineering, health and medicine, aeronautics and many other different industries.
[src:accelerometer-mems/piezoelectric-accelerometer] There are two common methods used to manufacture accelerometers.
[src:accelerometer-mems/piezoelectric-accelerometer] One is based upon the principles of piezoresistance and the other is based on the principles of piezoelectricity.
[src:accelerometer-mems/piezoelectric-accelerometer] Both methods ensure that unwanted orthogonal acceleration vectors are excluded from detection.
[src:accelerometer-mems/piezoelectric-accelerometer] Manufacturing an accelerometer that uses piezoresistance first starts with a semiconductor layer that is attached to a handle wafer by a thick oxide layer.
[src:accelerometer-mems/piezoelectric-accelerometer] The semiconductor layer is then patterned to the accelerometer's geometry.
[src:accelerometer-mems/piezoelectric-accelerometer] This semiconductor layer has one or more apertures so that the underlying mass will have the corresponding apertures.
[src:accelerometer-mems/piezoelectric-accelerometer] Next the semiconductor layer is used as a mask to etch out a cavity in the underlying thick oxide.
[src:accelerometer-mems/piezoelectric-accelerometer] A mass in the cavity is supported in cantilever fashion by the piezoresistant arms of the semiconductor layer.
[src:accelerometer-mems/piezoelectric-accelerometer] Directly below the accelerometer's geometry is a flex cavity that allows the mass in the cavity to flex or move in direction that is orthogonal to the surface of the accelerometer.
[src:accelerometer-mems/piezoelectric-accelerometer] Accelerometers based upon piezoelectricity are constructed with two piezoelectric transducers.
[src:accelerometer-mems/piezoelectric-accelerometer] The unit consists of a hollow tube that is sealed by a piezoelectric transducer on each end.
[src:accelerometer-mems/piezoelectric-accelerometer] The transducers are oppositely polarized and are selected to have a specific series capacitance.
[src:accelerometer-mems/piezoelectric-accelerometer] The tube is then partially filled with a heavy liquid and the accelerometer is excited.
[src:accelerometer-mems/piezoelectric-accelerometer] While excited the total output voltage is continuously measured and the volume of the heavy liquid is microadjusted until the desired output voltage is obtained.
[src:accelerometer-mems/piezoelectric-accelerometer] Finally the outputs of the individual transducers are measured, the residual voltage difference is tabulated, and the dominant transducer is identified.
[src:accelerometer-mems/piezoelectric-accelerometer] In 1943 the Danish company Brüel & Kjær launched Type 4301 - the world's first charge accelerometer.
[src:accelerometer-mems/piezoelectric-accelerometer] Piezoelectric accelerometers are used in many different industries, environments, and applications - all typically requiring measurement of short duration impulses.
[src:accelerometer-mems/piezoelectric-accelerometer] Piezoelectric measuring devices are widely used today in the laboratory, on the production floor, and as original equipment for measuring and recording dynamic changes in mechanical variables including shock and vibration.
[src:accelerometer-mems/piezoelectric-accelerometer] Some accelerometers have built-in electronics to amplify the signal before transmitting it to the recording device.
[src:accelerometer-mems/piezoelectric-accelerometer] This work was pioneered by PCB Piezotronics, released in 1967 as ICP® Integrated circuit piezoelectric, later evolving to be the IEPE standard (see Integrated Electronics Piezo-Electric).
[src:accelerometer-mems/piezoelectric-accelerometer] Other related, brand specific descriptors of IEPE are: CCLD, IsoTron or DeltaTron.
[src:accelerometer-mems/piezoelectric-accelerometer] Accelerometers also have had the addition of onboard memory to contain serial number and calibration data, typically referred to as TEDS Transducer Electronic Data Sheet per the IEEE 1451 standard.
[src:accelerometer-mems/proof-mass] A **proof mass** or **test mass** is a known quantity of mass used in a measuring instrument as a reference for the measurement of an unknown quantity.
[src:accelerometer-mems/proof-mass] A mass used to calibrate a weighing scale is sometimes called a *calibration mass* or *calibration weight*.
[src:accelerometer-mems/proof-mass] A proof mass that deforms a spring in an accelerometer is sometimes called the *seismic mass*.
[src:accelerometer-mems/proof-mass] In a convective accelerometer, a fluid proof mass may be employed.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] A **seismometer** is an instrument that responds to ground displacement and shaking caused by quakes, volcanic eruptions, and explosions.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] They are usually combined with a timing device and a recording device to form a **seismograph**.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] The output of such a device—formerly recorded on paper (see picture) or film, now recorded and processed digitally—is a seismogram.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] Such data is used to locate and characterize earthquakes, and to study the internal structure of Earth.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] A simple seismometer, sensitive to up-down motions of the Earth, is like a weight hanging from a spring, both suspended from a frame that moves along with any motion detected.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] The relative motion between the weight (called the mass) and the frame provides a measurement of the vertical ground motion.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] A rotating drum is attached to the frame and a pen is attached to the weight, thus recording any ground motion in a seismogram.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] Any movement from the ground moves the frame.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] The mass tends not to move because of its inertia, and by measuring the movement between the frame and the mass, the motion of the ground can be determined.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] Early seismometers used optical levers or mechanical linkages to amplify the small motions involved, recording on soot-covered paper or photographic paper.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] In some systems, the mass is held nearly motionless relative to the frame by an electronic negative feedback loop.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] The motion of the mass relative to the frame is measured, and the feedback loop applies a magnetic or electrostatic force to keep the mass nearly motionless.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] The voltage needed to produce this force is the output of the seismometer, which is recorded digitally.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] In other systems the weight is allowed to move, and its motion produces an electrical charge in a coil attached to the mass which voltage moves through the magnetic field of a magnet attached to the frame.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] This design is often used in a geophone, which is used in exploration for oil and gas.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] Seismic observatories usually have instruments measuring three axes: north-south (y-axis), east–west (x-axis), and vertical (z-axis).
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] If only one axis is measured, it is usually the vertical because it is less noisy and gives better records of some seismic waves.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] The foundation of a seismic station is critical.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] A professional station is sometimes mounted on bedrock.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] The best mountings may be in deep boreholes, which avoid thermal effects, ground noise and tilting from weather and tides.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] Other instruments are often mounted in insulated enclosures on small buried piers of unreinforced concrete.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] Reinforcing rods and aggregates would distort the pier as the temperature changes.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] A site is always surveyed for ground noise with a temporary installation before pouring the pier and laying conduit.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] Originally, European seismographs were placed in a particular area after a destructive earthquake.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] Today, they are spread to provide appropriate coverage (in the case of weak-motion seismology) or concentrated in high-risk regions (strong-motion seismology).
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] The word derives from the Greek σεισμός, *seismós*, a shaking or quake, from the verb σείω, *seíō*, to shake; and μέτρον, *métron*, to measure, and was coined by David Milne-Home in 1841, to describe an instrument designed by Scottish physicist James David Forbes.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] The technical discipline concerning such devices is called **seismometry**, a branch of seismology.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] The concept of measuring the "shaking" of something means that the word "seismograph" might be used in a more general sense.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] For example, a monitoring station that tracks changes in electromagnetic noise affecting amateur radio waves presents an *rf seismograph*.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] And helioseismology studies the "quakes" on the Sun.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] The first seismometer was made in China during the 2nd century.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] It was invented by Zhang Heng, a Chinese mathematician and astronomer.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] The first Western description of the device comes from the French physicist and priest Jean de Hautefeuille in 1703.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] The modern seismometer was developed in the 19th century.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] Seismometers were placed on the Moon starting in 1969 as part of the Apollo Lunar Surface Experiments Package.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] In December 2018, a seismometer was deployed on the planet Mars by the *InSight* lander, the first time a seismometer was placed onto the surface of another planet.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] Some secondary sources mention unverified claims that a device resembling an earthquake detector may have existed in Ancient Egypt, but as of January 2026, no reliable historical sources confirm this, and the earliest well-documented seismoscope was invented in China by Zhang Heng in AD 132.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] In AD 132, Zhang Heng of China's Han dynasty is said to have invented the first seismoscope (by the definition above), which was called *Houfeng Didong Yi* (translated as, "instrument for measuring the seasonal winds and the movements of the Earth").
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] The description we have, from the History of the Later Han Dynasty, says that it was a large bronze vessel, about 2 meters in diameter; at eight points around the top were dragon's heads holding bronze balls.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] When there was an earthquake, one of the dragons' mouths would open and drop its ball into a bronze toad at the base, making a sound and supposedly showing the direction of the earthquake.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] On at least one occasion, probably at the time of a large earthquake in Gansu in AD 143, the seismoscope indicated an earthquake even though one was not felt.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] The available text says that inside the vessel was a central column that could move along eight tracks; this is thought to refer to a pendulum, though it is not known exactly how this was linked to a mechanism that would open only one dragon's mouth.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] The first earthquake recorded by this seismoscope was supposedly "somewhere in the east".
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] Days later, a rider from the east reported this earthquake.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] By the 13th century, seismographic devices existed in the Maragheh observatory (founded 1259) in Persia, though it is unclear whether these were constructed independently or based on the first seismoscope.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] French physicist and priest Jean de Hautefeuille described a seismoscope in 1703, which used a bowl filled with mercury which would spill into one of eight receivers equally spaced around the bowl, though there is no evidence that he actually constructed the device.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] A mercury seismoscope was constructed in 1784 or 1785 by Atanasio Cavalli, a copy of which can be found at the University Library in Bologna, and a further mercury seismoscope was constructed by Niccolò Cacciatore in 1818.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] James Lind also built a seismological tool of unknown design or efficacy (known as an earthquake machine) in the late 1790s.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] Pendulum devices were developing at the same time.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] Neapolitan naturalist Nicola Cirillo set up a network of pendulum earthquake detectors following the 1731 Puglia Earthquake, where the amplitude was detected using a protractor to measure the swinging motion.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] Benedictine monk Andrea Bina further developed this concept in 1751, having the pendulum create trace marks in sand under the mechanism, providing both magnitude and direction of motion.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] Neapolitan clockmaker Domenico Salsano produced a similar pendulum which recorded using a paintbrush in 1783, labelling it a *geo-sismometro*, possibly the first use of a similar word to *seismometer*.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] Naturalist Nicolo Zupo devised an instrument to detect electrical disturbances and earthquakes at the same time (1784).
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] The first moderately successful device for detecting the time of an earthquake was devised by Ascanio Filomarino in 1796, who improved upon Salsano's pendulum instrument, using a pencil to mark, and using a hair attached to the mechanism to inhibit the motion of a clock's balance wheel.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] This meant that the clock would only start once an earthquake took place, allowing determination of the time of incidence.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] After an earthquake taking place on October 4, 1834, Luigi Pagani observed that the mercury seismoscope held at Bologna University had completely spilled over, and did not provide useful information.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] He therefore devised a portable device that used lead shot to detect the direction of an earthquake, where the lead fell into four bins arranged in a circle, to determine the quadrant of earthquake incidence.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] In response to a series of earthquakes near Comrie in Scotland in 1839, a committee was formed in the United Kingdom in order to produce better detection devices for earthquakes.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] The outcome of this was an inverted pendulum seismometer constructed by James David Forbes, first presented in a report by David Milne-Home in 1842, which recorded the measurements of seismic activity through the use of a pencil placed on paper above the pendulum.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] The designs provided did not prove effective, according to Milne's reports.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] It was Milne who coined the word *seismometer* in 1841, to describe this instrument.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] In 1843, the first horizontal pendulum was used in a seismometer, reported by Milne (though it is unclear if he was the original inventor).
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] After these inventions, Robert Mallet published an 1848 paper where he suggested ideas for seismometer design, suggesting that such a device would need to register time, record amplitudes horizontally and vertically, and ascertain direction.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] His suggested design was funded, and construction was attempted, but his final design did not fulfill his expectations and suffered from the same problems as the Forbes design, being inaccurate and not self-recording.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] Karl Kreil constructed a seismometer in Prague between 1848 and 1850, which used a point-suspended rigid cylindrical pendulum covered in paper, drawn upon by a fixed pencil.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] The cylinder was rotated every 24 hours, providing an approximate time for a given quake.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] Luigi Palmieri, influenced by Mallet's 1848 paper, invented a seismometer in 1856 that could record the time of an earthquake.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] This device used metallic pendulums which closed an electric circuit with vibration, which then powered an electromagnet to stop a clock.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] Palmieri seismometers were widely distributed and used for a long time.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] By 1872, a committee in the United Kingdom led by James Bryce expressed their dissatisfaction with the current available seismometers, still using the large 1842 Forbes device located in Comrie Parish Church, and requested a seismometer which was compact, easy to install and easy to read.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] In 1875 they settled on a large example of the Mallet device, consisting of an array of cylindrical pins of various sizes installed at right angles to each other on a sand bed, where larger earthquakes would knock down larger pins.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] This device was constructed in 'Earthquake House' near Comrie, which can be considered the world's first purpose-built seismological observatory.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] As of 2013, no earthquake has been large enough to cause any of the cylinders to fall in either the original device or replicas.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] The first seismographs were invented in the 1870s and 1880s.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] The first seismograph was produced by Filippo Cecchi in around 1875.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] A seismoscope would trigger the device to begin recording, and then a recording surface would produce a graphical illustration of the tremors automatically (a seismogram).
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] However, the instrument was not sensitive enough, and the first seismogram produced by the instrument was in 1887, by which time John Milne had already demonstrated his design in Japan.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] In 1880, the first horizontal pendulum seismometer was developed by the team of John Milne, James Alfred Ewing and Thomas Gray, who worked as foreign-government advisors in Japan, from 1880 to 1895.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] Milne, Ewing and Gray, all having been hired by the Meiji Government in the previous five years to assist Japan's modernization efforts, founded the Seismological Society of Japan in response to an Earthquake that took place on February 22, 1880, at Yokohama (Yokohama earthquake).
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] Two instruments were constructed by Ewing over the next year, one being a common-pendulum seismometer and the other being the first seismometer using a damped horizontal pendulum.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] The innovative recording system allowed for a continuous record, the first to do so.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] The first seismogram was recorded on 3 November 1880 on both of Ewing's instruments.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] Modern seismometers would eventually descend from these designs.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] Milne has been referred to as the 'Father of modern seismology' and his seismograph design has been called the first modern seismometer.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] This produced the first effective measurement of horizontal motion.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] Gray would produce the first reliable method for recording vertical motion, which produced the first effective 3-axis recordings.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] An early special-purpose seismometer consisted of a large, stationary pendulum, with a stylus on the bottom.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] As the earth started to move, the heavy mass of the pendulum had the inertia to stay still within the frame.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] The result is that the stylus scratched a pattern corresponding with the Earth's movement.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] This type of strong-motion seismometer recorded upon a smoked glass (glass with carbon soot).
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] While not sensitive enough to detect distant earthquakes, this instrument could indicate the direction of the pressure waves and thus help find the epicenter of a local quake.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] Such instruments were useful in the analysis of the 1906 San Francisco earthquake.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] Further analysis was performed in the 1980s, using these early recordings, enabling a more precise determination of the initial fault break location in Marin county and its subsequent progression, mostly to the south.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] Later, professional suites of instruments for the worldwide standard seismographic network had one set of instruments tuned to oscillate at fifteen seconds, and the other at ninety seconds, each set measuring in three directions.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] Amateurs or observatories with limited means tuned their smaller, less sensitive instruments to ten seconds.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] The basic damped horizontal pendulum seismometer swings like the gate of a fence.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] A heavy weight is mounted on the point of a long (from 10 cm to several meters) triangle, hinged at its vertical edge.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] As the ground moves, the weight stays unmoving, swinging the "gate" on the hinge.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] The advantage of a horizontal pendulum is that it achieves very low frequencies of oscillation in a compact instrument.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] The "gate" is slightly tilted, so the weight tends to slowly return to a central position.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] The pendulum is adjusted (before the damping is installed) to oscillate once per three seconds, or once per thirty seconds.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] The general-purpose instruments of small stations or amateurs usually oscillate once per ten seconds.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] A pan of oil is placed under the arm, and a small sheet of metal mounted on the underside of the arm drags in the oil to damp oscillations.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] The level of oil, position on the arm, and angle and size of sheet is adjusted until the damping is "critical", that is, almost having oscillation.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] The hinge is very low friction, often torsion wires, so the only friction is the internal friction of the wire.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] Small seismographs with low proof masses are placed in a vacuum to reduce disturbances from air currents.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] Zollner described torsionally suspended horizontal pendulums as early as 1869, but developed them for gravimetry rather than seismometry.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] Early seismometers had an arrangement of levers on jeweled bearings, to scratch smoked glass or paper.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] Later, mirrors reflected a light beam to a direct-recording plate or roll of photographic paper.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] Briefly, some designs returned to mechanical movements to save money.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] In mid-twentieth-century systems, the light was reflected to a pair of differential electronic photosensors called a photomultiplier.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] The voltage generated in the photomultiplier was used to drive galvanometers which had a small mirror mounted on the axis.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] The moving reflected light beam would strike the surface of the turning drum, which was covered with photo-sensitive paper.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] The expense of developing photo-sensitive paper caused many seismic observatories to switch to ink or thermal-sensitive paper.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] After World War II, the seismometers developed by Milne, Ewing and Gray were adapted into the widely used Press-Ewing seismometer.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] Modern instruments use electronic sensors, amplifiers, and recording devices.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] Most are broadband covering a wide range of frequencies.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] Some seismometers can measure motions with frequencies from 500 Hz to 0.00118 Hz (1/500 = 0.002 seconds per cycle, to 1/0.00118 = 850 seconds per cycle).
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] The mechanical suspension for horizontal instruments remains the garden-gate described above.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] Vertical instruments use some kind of constant-force suspension, such as the LaCoste suspension.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] The LaCoste suspension uses a zero-length spring to provide a long period (high sensitivity).
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] Some modern instruments use a "triaxial" or "Galperin" design, in which three identical motion sensors are set at the same angle to the vertical but 120 degrees apart on the horizontal.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] Vertical and horizontal motions can be computed from the outputs of the three sensors.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] Seismometers unavoidably introduce some distortion into the signals they measure, but professionally designed systems have carefully characterized frequency transforms.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] Modern sensitivities come in three broad ranges: geophones, 50 to 750 V/m; local geologic seismographs, about 1,500 V/m; and teleseismographs, used for world survey, about 20,000 V/m.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] Instruments come in three main varieties: short-period, long-period and broadband.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] The short- and long-period instruments measure velocity and are very sensitive; however they 'clip' the signal or go off-scale for ground motion that is strong enough to be felt by people.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] A 24-bit analog-to-digital conversion channel is commonplace.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] Practical devices are linear to roughly one part per million.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] Delivered seismometers come with two styles of output: analog and digital.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] Analog seismographs require analog recording equipment, possibly including an analog-to-digital converter.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] The output of a digital seismograph can be simply input to a computer.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] It presents the data in a standard digital format (often "SE2" over Ethernet).
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] The modern broadband seismograph can record a very broad range of frequencies.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] It consists of a small "proof mass", confined by electrical forces, driven by sophisticated electronics.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] As the earth moves, the electronics attempt to hold the mass steady through a feedback circuit.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] The amount of force necessary to achieve this is then recorded.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] In most designs the electronics holds a mass motionless relative to the frame.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] This device is called a "force balance accelerometer".
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] It measures acceleration instead of velocity of ground movement.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] Basically, the distance between the mass and some part of the frame is measured very precisely, by a linear variable differential transformer.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] Some instruments use a linear variable differential capacitor.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] That measurement is then amplified by electronic amplifiers attached to parts of an electronic negative feedback loop.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] One of the amplified currents from the negative feedback loop drives a coil very like a loudspeaker.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] The result is that the mass stays nearly motionless.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] Most instruments measure directly the ground motion using the distance sensor.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] The voltage generated in a sense coil on the mass by the magnet directly measures the instantaneous velocity of the ground.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] The current to the drive coil provides a sensitive, accurate measurement of the force between the mass and frame, thus measuring directly the ground's acceleration (using f=ma where f=force, m=mass, a=acceleration).
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] One of the continuing problems with sensitive vertical seismographs is the buoyancy of their masses.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] The uneven changes in pressure caused by wind blowing on an open window can easily change the density of the air in a room enough to cause a vertical seismograph to show spurious signals.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] Therefore, most professional seismographs are sealed in rigid gas-tight enclosures.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] For example, this is why a common Streckeisen model has a thick glass base that must be glued to its pier without bubbles in the glue.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] It might seem logical to make the heavy magnet serve as a mass, but that subjects the seismograph to errors when the Earth's magnetic field moves.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] This is also why seismograph's moving parts are constructed from a material that interacts minimally with magnetic fields.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] A seismograph is also sensitive to changes in temperature so many instruments are constructed from low expansion materials such as nonmagnetic invar.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] The hinges on a seismograph are usually patented, and by the time the patent has expired, the design has been improved.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] The most successful public domain designs use thin foil hinges in a clamp.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] Another issue is that the transfer function of a seismograph must be accurately characterized, so that its frequency response is known.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] This is often the crucial difference between professional and amateur instruments.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] Most are characterized on a variable frequency shaking table.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] Another type of seismometer is a digital strong-motion seismometer, or accelerograph.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] The data from such an instrument is essential to understand how an earthquake affects man-made structures, through earthquake engineering.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] The recordings of such instruments are crucial for the assessment of seismic hazard, through engineering seismology.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] A strong-motion seismometer measures acceleration.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] This can be mathematically integrated later to give velocity and position.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] Strong-motion seismometers are not as sensitive to ground motions as teleseismic instruments but they stay on scale during the strongest seismic shaking.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] Strong motion sensors are used for intensity meter applications.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] Accelerographs and geophones are often heavy cylindrical magnets with a spring-mounted coil inside.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] As the case moves, the coil tends to stay stationary, so the magnetic field cuts the wires, inducing current in the output wires.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] They receive frequencies from several hundred hertz down to 1 Hz.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] Some have electronic damping, a low-budget way to get some of the performance of the closed-loop wide-band geologic seismographs.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] Strain-beam accelerometers constructed as integrated circuits are too insensitive for geologic seismographs (2002), but are widely used in geophones.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] Some other sensitive designs measure the current generated by the flow of a non-corrosive ionic fluid through an electret sponge or a conductive fluid through a magnetic field.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] Seismometers spaced in a seismic array can also be used to precisely locate, in three dimensions, the source of an earthquake, using the time it takes for seismic waves to propagate away from the hypocenter, the initiating point of fault rupture (See also Earthquake location).
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] Interconnected seismometers are also used, as part of the International Monitoring System to detect underground nuclear test explosions, as well as for Earthquake early warning systems.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] These seismometers are often used as part of a large-scale governmental or scientific project, but some organizations such as the Quake-Catcher Network, can use residential size detectors built into computers to detect earthquakes as well.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] In reflection seismology, an array of seismometers image sub-surface features.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] The data are reduced to images using algorithms similar to tomography.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] The data reduction methods resemble those of computer-aided tomographic medical imaging X-ray machines (CAT-scans), or imaging sonars.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] A worldwide array of seismometers can actually image the interior of the Earth in wave-speed and transmissivity.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] This type of system uses events such as earthquakes, impact events or nuclear explosions as wave sources.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] The first efforts at this method used manual data reduction from paper seismograph charts.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] Modern digital seismograph records are better adapted to direct computer use.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] With inexpensive seismometer designs and internet access, amateurs and small institutions have even formed a "public seismograph network".
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] Seismographic systems used for petroleum or other mineral exploration historically used an explosive and a wireline of geophones unrolled behind a truck.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] Now most short-range systems use "thumpers" that hit the ground, and some small commercial systems have such good digital signal processing that a few sledgehammer strikes provide enough signal for short-distance refractive surveys.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] Exotic cross or two-dimensional arrays of geophones are sometimes used to perform three-dimensional reflective imaging of subsurface features.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] Basic linear refractive geomapping software (once a black art) is available off-the-shelf, running on laptop computers, using strings as small as three geophones.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] Some systems now come in an 18" (0.5 m) plastic field case with a computer, display and printer in the cover.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] Small seismic imaging systems are now sufficiently inexpensive to be used by civil engineers to survey foundation sites, locate bedrock, and find subsurface water.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] A new technique for detecting earthquakes has been found, using fiber optic cables.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] In 2016 a team of metrologists running frequency metrology experiments in England observed noise with a wave-form resembling the seismic waves generated by earthquakes.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] This was found to match seismological observations of an Mw 6.0 earthquake in Italy, ~1400 km away.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] Further experiments in England, Italy, and with a submarine fiber optic cable to Malta detected additional earthquakes, including one 4,100 km away, and an ML 3.4 earthquake 89 km away from the cable.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] Seismic waves are detectable because they cause micrometer-scale changes in the length of the cable.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] As the length changes so does the time it takes a packet of light to traverse to the far end of the cable and back (using a second fiber).
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] Using ultra-stable metrology-grade lasers, these extremely minute shifts of timing (on the order of femtoseconds) appear as phase-changes.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] This point is also the point closest to the earthquake's epicenter, which should be on a plane perpendicular to the cable.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] The difference between the P wave/S wave arrival times provides a distance (under ideal conditions), constraining the epicenter to a circle.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] A second detection on a non-parallel cable is needed to resolve the ambiguity of the resulting solution.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] Additional observations constrain the location of the earthquake's epicenter, and may resolve the depth.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] This technique is expected to be a boon in observing earthquakes, especially the smaller ones, in vast portions of the global ocean where there are no seismometers, and at much lower cost than ocean-bottom seismometers.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] Researchers at Stanford University created a deep-learning algorithm called UrbanDenoiser which can detect earthquakes, particularly in urban cities.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] The algorithm filters out the background noise from the seismic noise gathered from busy cities in urban areas to detect earthquakes.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] Today, the most common recorder is a computer with an analog-to-digital converter, a disk drive and an internet connection; for amateurs, a PC with a sound card and associated software is adequate.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] Most systems record continuously, but some record only when a signal is detected, as shown by a short-term increase in the variation of the signal, compared to its long-term average (which can vary slowly because of changes in seismic noise), also known as a STA/LTA trigger.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] Prior to the availability of digital processing of seismic data in the late 1970s, the records were done in a few different forms on different types of media.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] A "Helicorder" drum was a device used to record data into photographic paper or in the form of paper and ink.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] A "Develocorder" was a machine that record data from up to 20 channels into a 16-mm film.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] The recorded film can be viewed by a machine.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] The reading and measuring from these types of media can be done by hand.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] After the digital processing has been used, the archives of the seismic data were recorded in magnetic tapes.
[src:accelerometer-mems/seismometer] Due to the deterioration of older magnetic tape medias, large number of waveforms from the archives are not recoverable.
